      "account_id" : 6555365,
      "reputation" : 2073,
      "user_id" : 5068213,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 86,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/053adbffbd92d2dc16a37bee857c2a15?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Bharti Rawat",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5068213/bharti-rawat"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 49,
    "last_activity_date" : 1551937593,
    "last_edit_date" : 1551937593,
    "creation_date" : 1465019126,
    "answer_id" : 37626811,
    "question_id" : 12737293,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In <strong>Ubuntu/Unix</strong> we can resolve this problem in 2 steps as described below.</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>Type <code>netstat -plten |grep java</code></p>\n\n<p>This will give an output similar to:</p>\n\n<pre><code>tcp   0   0 0.0.0.0:8080   0.0.0.0:*  LISTEN   1001  76084  9488/java       \n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Here <code>8080</code> is the port number at which the java process is listening and <code>9488</code> is its process id (pid).</p></li>\n<li><p>In order to free the occupied port, we have to kill this process using the <code>kill</code> command.</p>\n\n<pre><code>kill -9 9488\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><code>9488</code> is the process id from earlier. We use <code>-9</code> to force stop the process. </p></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>Your port should now be free and you can restart the server.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3311832,
      "reputation" : 410,
      "user_id" : 2785156,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 17,
      "profile_image" : "https://graph.facebook.com/100000161364149/picture?type=large",
      "display_name" : "Chetan Gowda",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2785156/chetan-gowda"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1468837064,
    "creation_date" : 1468837064,
    "answer_id" : 38434178,
    "question_id" : 12737293,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I faced similar issue in Eclipse when two consoles were opened when I started the Server program first and then the Client program. I used to stop the program in the single console thinking that it had closed the server, but it had only closed the client and not the server. I found running Java processes in my Task manager. This problem was solved by closing both Server and Client programs from their individual consoles(Eclipse shows console of latest active program). So when I started the Server program again, the port was again open to be captured.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 8845091,
      "reputation" : 469,
      "user_id" : 6606123,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-KAD3EdCg20k/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAFUM/ABN5Z6IInWw/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
      "display_name" : "suketup",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6606123/suketup"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1471507276,
    "creation_date" : 1471507276,
    "answer_id" : 39012816,
    "question_id" : 12737293,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Your port must be busy in some Other Process. So you can download TCPView on <a href=\"https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb897437\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb897437</a> and kill the process for used port.</p>\n\n<p>If you don't know your port, double click on the server that is not starting and click on Open Server Properties Page and click on glassfish from left column. You will find the ports here.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3100005,
      "reputation" : 697,
      "user_id" : 2624378,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 17,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/y5byk.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "tonysok",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2624378/tonysok"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1487353435,
    "creation_date" : 1487353435,
    "answer_id" : 42304286,
    "question_id" : 12737293,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>(1) check the port is in use or not, kill that process</p>\n\n<p><strong>$ lsof -i:[port]</strong></p>\n\n<p>(2) another reason is the port is used by ipv6, solution:</p>\n\n<p>edit <strong>/etc/sysctl.conf</strong> </p>\n\n<p>add this to the file</p>\n\n<p><strong>net.ipv6.conf.all.disable_ipv6 = 1</strong></p>\n\n<p>then make it effect</p>\n\n<p><strong>$ sudo sysctl -p /etc/sysctl.conf</strong> </p>\n\n<p>or just reboot</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9642232,
      "reputation" : 461,
      "user_id" : 7156103,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0520d8e170f503fd7d2c3d0b5e72abb1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Vibhav Chaddha",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7156103/vibhav-chaddha"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 11,
    "last_activity_date" : 1487922407,
    "creation_date" : 1487922407,
    "answer_id" : 42433250,
    "question_id" : 12737293,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>For those who are looking for the <strong>simplest of the answers</strong> (as that is what we usually miss), just stop your running project and start it again.\nMost of the time what we do is we forget to stop the project we ran earlier and when we re-run the project it shows such an issue. </p>\n\n<p>I am also attaching a photo to make it clearer (I use 'Spring tool suite').\nSo what you need to do is either click the button on the extreme right, if you want to relaunch the same project or first click on the button which is 2nd from the right to stop your project and then the button on the extreme left to run your project. I hope this will solve the issue of few of the newer programmers. :)</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/eXGMh.png\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/eXGMh.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 8203737,
      "reputation" : 2455,
      "user_id" : 6174209,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 83,
      "profile_image" : "https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-jHLU6Iwuhyk/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAALA/00187AZJs7k/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
      "display_name" : "Yasitha Bandara",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6174209/yasitha-bandara"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1504424355,
    "creation_date" : 1504424355,
    "answer_id" : 46021269,
    "question_id" : 12737293,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Yes, as Guido Simone said it because another process listening to the same port.If you are in Ubuntu You can simply kill that process giving command\n<code>sudo kill $(sudo lsof -t -i:[port number])</code></p>\n\n<p>ex: <code>sudo kill $(sudo lsof -t -i:8080)</code></p>\n\n<p>But once it didn't work for me.\ni gave the command</p>\n\n<pre><code>$ lsof -i:[port] \n</code></pre>\n\n<p>and it shows nothing. </p>\n\n<p>I checked my docker containers using command\n<code>docker ps -a</code> but non of them alive.All containers has stopped\n(but i remember ,i stopped one container which was used same port few minutes ago.).To make sure that docker is not the reason,I stop whole docker process using command <code>sudo service docker stop</code> and try again.\nSurprisingly eclipse didn't show the error at that time .It run my program perfectly.</p>\n\n<p>Hope my experience will help some one.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2270396,
      "reputation" : 1045,
      "user_id" : 1997983,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/qm5vY.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Rakesh Burbure",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1997983/rakesh-burbure"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1517383927,
    "creation_date" : 1517383927,
    "answer_id" : 48536792,
    "question_id" : 12737293,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>It means some other process is already using the port. In case if this port is being used by some other critical applications and you don't want to close that application, the better way is to choose any other port which is free to use. </p>\n\n<p>Configure your application to use any other port which is free and you will see your application working.</p>\n"
  }, {
